📦 2. Lists in Python

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is a List?

```text id="list_def"
A list is an ordered and mutable collection of items.
```

---

💻 List Example

```python id="list_example2"
numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40]

print(numbers)
print(type(numbers))
```

---

🔄 Access List Elements

```python id="list_access"
fruits = ["Apple", "Mango", "Banana"]

print(fruits[0])
print(fruits[-1])
```

---

➕ Add Elements to List

```python id="list_append"
fruits = ["Apple", "Mango"]

fruits.append("Orange")

print(fruits)
```

---

❌ Remove Elements

```python id="list_remove"
numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4]

numbers.remove(2)

print(numbers)
```

---

🔧 Common List Methods

| Method      | Purpose         |
| ----------- | --------------- |
| `append()`  | Add item        |
| `remove()`  | Remove item     |
| `pop()`     | Remove by index |
| `sort()`    | Sort list       |
| `reverse()` | Reverse list    |

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📦 3. Tuples in Python

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is a Tuple?

```text id="tuple_def2"
A tuple is an ordered and immutable collection of items.
```

---

💻 Tuple Example

```python id="tuple_example2"
coordinates = (10, 20)

print(coordinates)
print(type(coordinates))
```

---

⚠️ Tuple Immutability

Tuples cannot be modified after creation.

---

❌ Example

```python id="tuple_error"
data = (1, 2, 3)

data[0] = 10
```

---

📌 Tuple Advantages

✔ Faster than lists
✔ Immutable
✔ Safer for fixed data

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🗂️ 4. Dictionaries in Python

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is a Dictionary?

```text id="dict_def"
A dictionary stores data in key-value pairs.
```

---

💻 Dictionary Example

```python id="dict_example2"
student = {
    "name": "Saakshi",
    "age": 22,
    "course": "Python"
}

print(student)
```

---

🔍 Access Dictionary Values

```python id="dict_access"
student = {
    "name": "Alex",
    "age": 21
}

print(student["name"])
```

---

➕ Add New Key-Value Pair

```python id="dict_add"
student = {
    "name": "Sam"
}

student["age"] = 20

print(student)
```

---

🔧 Common Dictionary Methods

| Method     | Purpose             |
| ---------- | ------------------- |
| `keys()`   | Get all keys        |
| `values()` | Get all values      |
| `items()`  | Get key-value pairs |
| `get()`    | Access value safely |
| `pop()`    | Remove item         |

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔄 5. Sets in Python

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is a Set?

```text id="set_def"
A set is an unordered collection of unique items.
```

---

💻 Set Example

```python id="set_example2"
numbers = {1, 2, 3, 3, 4}

print(numbers)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="set_output"
{1, 2, 3, 4}
```

---

➕ Add Elements to Set

```python id="set_add"
languages = {"Python", "Java"}

languages.add("C++")

print(languages)
```

---

❌ Remove Elements from Set

```python id="set_remove"
numbers = {1, 2, 3}

numbers.remove(2)

print(numbers)
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔧 Common Set Methods

| Method           | Purpose          |
| ---------------- | ---------------- |
| `add()`          | Add element      |
| `remove()`       | Remove element   |
| `clear()`        | Remove all items |
| `union()`        | Combine sets     |
| `intersection()` | Common elements  |

---

⚖️ Difference Between Collections

| Collection | Ordered | Mutable | Unique Values |
| ---------- | ------- | ------- | ------------- |
| List       | ✔       | ✔       | ❌             |
| Tuple      | ✔       | ❌       | ❌             |
| Set        | ❌       | ✔       | ✔             |
| Dictionary | ✔       | ✔       | Keys unique   |

---

